ber.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EYet%2C%20there%20was%20another%20inspiration%20for%20Christie%E2%80%99s%20story%3A%20Arthur%20Conan%20Doyle%E2%80%99s%20Sherlock%20Holmes%20novel%2C%20%3Cem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.britannica.com%2Ftopic%2FThe-Hound-of-the-Baskervilles%5C%22%3EThe%20Hound%20of%20the%20Baskervilles%3C%2Fa%3E%20%3C%2Fem%3E(1902).%20Christie%20draws%20on%20Conan%20Doyle%E2%80%99s%20novel%20in%20the%20design%20and%20unpacking%20of%20the%20alleged%20curse%20which%2C%20in%20both%20stories%2C%20actually%20turns%20out%20to%20be%20a%20sophisticated%20crime%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EChristie%20was%20familiar%20with%20Egypt%2C%20having%20stayed%20for%20three%20months%20in%20Cairo%20with%20her%20mother%20in%201910.%20%3Cem%3EThe%20Adventure%20of%20the%20Egyptian%20Tomb%3C%2Fem%3E%20deliberately%20references%20Carnarvon%E2%80%99s%20death%20at%20her%20story%E2%80%99s%20outset%2C%20channelling%20%E2%80%9CTutmania%E2%80%9D%20and%20the%20alleged%20curse%20into%20her%20fiction.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EPoirot%20is%20summoned%20by%20Lady%20Willard%2C%20the%20widow%20of%20Sir%20John%20Willard%2C%20who%20died%20shortly%20after%20excavating%20%E2%80%9Cfunereal%20chambers%E2%80%9D%20near%20the%20%E2%80%9CPyramids%20of%20Gizeh%E2%80%9D.%20Willard%E2%80%99s%20death%2C%20coupled%20with%20the%20deaths%20of%20others%20on%20the%20dig%2C%20becomes%20the%20talk%20of%20the%20day.%20As%20the%20narrator%2C%20Arthur%20Hastings%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.gutenberg.org%2Ffiles%2F61262%2F61262-h%2F61262-h.htm%5C%22%3Eobserves%3C%2Fa%3E%3A%20%E2%80%9CThe%20magic%20power%20of%20dead-and-gone%20Egypt%20was%20exalted%20to%20a%20fetish%20point.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EWhile%20Willard%20died%20of%20heart%20failure%2C%20Poirot%20reveals%20that%20a%20member%20of%20the%20dig%20team%2C%20Dr%20Ames%2C%20had%20been%20exploiting%20Willard%E2%80%99s%20death%20to%20harness%20the%20power%20of%20superstition%20and%20kill%20for%20financial%20gain.%20In%20this%20regard%2C%20and%20in%20others%2C%20the%20story%20mirrors%20%3Cem%3EThe%20Hound%20of%20the%20Baskervilles%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20in%20which%20a%20murderer%20excavates%20a%20family%20curse%20as%20a%20cover%20for%20their%20crime%2C%20in%20an%20attempt%20to%20acquire%20Baskerville%20Hall.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EThe%20power%20of%20superstition%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20murderers%20of%20both%20stories%20rely%20on%20superstition%20to%20shield%20them.%20The%20Baskerville%20family%20live%20with%20a%20curse%20involving%20a%20gigantic%20hound.%20It%20allegedly%20haunts%20the%20family%20after%20the%20evil%20Sir%20Hugo%20Baskerville%20pursued%20a%20woman%20across%20the%20moors%20to%20her%20death.%20The%20legend%20is%20passed%20through%20generations%20of%20the%20Baskerville%20family.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ESir%20Hugo%E2%80%99s%20descendent%2C%20Stapleton%2C%20who%20is%20third%20in%20line%20to%20the%20Baskerville%20estate%2C%20deploys%20the%20power%20of%20the%20curse.%20He%20creates%20his%20own%20demon%20hound%20by%20painting%20a%20large%20dog%E2%80%99s%20fur%20with%20blue%20luminescent%20paint%20and%20releasing%20it%20onto%20the%20moors.%20The%20sight%20of%20what%20looks%20like%20the%20demon%20hound%20kills%20the%20owner%20of%20Baskerville%20Hall%2C%20Sir%20Charles.%20He%20dies%2C%20like%20Willard%20in%20Christie%E2%80%99s%20story%2C%20of%20heart%20failure.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EBut%20it%20is%20how%20the%20detectives%20respond%20to%20superstition%20which%20cements%20the%20connections%20between%20the%20Conan%20Doyle%20and%20Christie%20stories.%20Both%20sleuths%20utilise%20superstition%20to%20expose%20the%20villains.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%20The%20Hound%20of%20the%20Baskervilles%2C%20Holmes%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.gutenberg.org%2Ffiles%2F2852%2F2852-h%2F2852-h.htm%5C%22%3Ewarns%20the%20new%20heir%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20Sir%20Henry%2C%20of%20the%20demon%20legend%20to%20keep%20him%20off%20the%20moor%3A%20%E2%80%9CBear%20in%20mind%2C%20Sir%20Henry%2C%20one%20of%20the%20phrases%20in%20that%20queer%20old%20legend%20%E2%80%A6%20and%20avoid%20the%20moor%20in%20those%20hours%20of%20darkness%20when%20the%20powers%20of%20evil%20are%20exalted.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EHolmes%20knows%2C%20although%20we%20do%20not%2C%20that%20the%20moor%20is%20dangerous%20for%20a%20Baskerville.%20Not%20because%20anything%20supernatural%20is%20afoot%2C%20but%20because%20the%20threat%20comes%20from%20a%20dangerous%20living%20animal%20and%20its%20murderous%20master.%20When%20Holmes%20tricks%20Stapleton%20into%20revealing%20his%20hound%2C%20the%20curse%20is%20laid%20to%20rest.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ESimilarly%2C%20Poirot%20confirms%20that%20he%20believes%20%E2%80%9Cin%20the%20terrific%20force%20of%20superstition%E2%80%9D.%20And%20on%20the%20dig%20site%20he%20has%20a%20trustworthy%20member%20of%20the%20team%20disguise%20himself%20as%20Anubis%2C%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20jackal-headed%2C%20the%20god%20of%20departing%20souls%E2%80%9D%2C%20to%20bring%20the%20case%20to%20a%20crisis%20point%20and%20unveil%20the%20villain.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EConan%20Doyle%E2%80%99s%20%E2%80%9Celementals%E2%80%9D%20and%20Christie%E2%80%99s%20archaeology%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20first%20publication%20of%20his%20story%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fdetails%2Fhoundofbaskervil00doyluoft%2Fpage%2Fn9%2Fmode%2F2up%5C%22%3EConan%20Doyle%20noted%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20he%20%E2%80%9Cowed%20its%20inception%E2%80%9D%20to%20Bertram%20Fletcher%20Robinson.%20The%20journalist%20had%20told%20him%20about%20an%20evil%20Devonshire%20squire%2C%20Richard%20Cabell%2C%20who%20died%20in%201677.%20His%20ghost%2C%20surrounded%20by%20fiendish%20hounds%2C%20was%20reputedly%20seen%20on%20the%20moors.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EAround%20the%20same%20time%2C%20Robinson%20was%20researching%20the%20misfortunes%20that%20befell%20those%20who%20handled%20an%20ancient%20Egyptian%20artefact%20known%20as%20the%20%E2%80%9Cunlucky%20mummy%E2%80%9D%20but%20that%20was%20actually%20a%20wooden%20board%20used%20to%20cover%20a%20mummy%20and%20painted%20to%20look%20like%20the%20person%20when%20they%20were%20alive.%20He%20died%20shortly%20afterwards.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EChristie%E2%80%99s%20%3Cem%3EThe%20Adventure%20of%20the%20Egyptian%20Tomb%3C%2Fem%3E%20also%20refers%20to%20the%20%E2%80%9Cunlucky%20mummy%E2%80%9D%2C%20saying%20it%20was%20%E2%80%9Cdragged%20out%20with%20fresh%20zest%E2%80%9D%20when%20Willard%20died%20after%20entering%20the%20tomb%20of%20%E2%80%9CKing%20Men-her-Ra%E2%80%9D.%20Even%20today%2C%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.britishmuseum.org%2Fcollection%2Fobject%2FY_EA22542%5C%22%3EBritish%20Museum%20confirms%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20the%20object%20has%20a%20%E2%80%9Creputation%20for%20bringing%20misfortune%E2%80%9D%2C%20though%20it%20explains%20that%20this%20has%20no%20%E2%80%9Cbasis%20in%20fact%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EConan%20Doyle%20reported%20to%20the%20press%20that%20an%20%E2%80%9Cevil%20element%E2%80%9D%20might%20have%20caused%20Carnavon%E2%80%99s%20%E2%80%9Cfatal%20illness%E2%80%9D%20and%20connected%20his%20death%20with%20Robinson%E2%80%99s.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.visitportsmouth.co.uk%2Fconan-doyle%2Fblog%2Fread%2F2023%2F03%2Fconan-doyle-and-king-tut-b86%5C%22%3EConan%20Doyle%20observed%3C%2Fa%3E%3A%20%E2%80%9COne%20does%20not%20know%20what%20elementals%20existed%20in%20those%20days%2C%20nor%20what%20their%20form%20might%20be.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EChristie%E2%80%99s%20story%20demonstrates%20her%20engagement%20with%20Conan%20Doyle%E2%80%99s%20writing%2C%20as%20well%20as%20her%20interest%20in%20Egypt.%20A%20decade%20later%20she%20became%20an%20amateur%20archaeologist%2C%20supporting%20the%20digs%20of%20her%20archaeologist%20husband%2C%20Max%20Mallowan%2C%20in%20the%20Middle%20East.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EChristie%E2%80%99s%20story%20also%20taps%20into%20the%20global%20interest%20in%20Tutankhamun.%20By%20the%20early%201920s%2C%20Conan%20Doyle%20%E2%80%93%20though%20still%20publishing%20Sherlock%20Holmes%20stories%20%E2%80%93%20was%20coming%20to%20the%20end%20of%20his%20career%2C%20while%20Christie%E2%80%99s%20was%20just%20beginning.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20final%20decade%20of%20his%20life%2C%20Conan%20Doyle%20embraced%20spiritualism%2C%20a%20religious%20movement%20that%20proclaimed%20the%20dead%20could%20communicate%20with%20the%20living.%20This%20opened%20him%20to%20the%20idea%20of%20ancient%20curses.%20He%20was%2C%20in%20the%20words%20of%20Sherlock%20Holmes%20in%20%3Cem%3EThe%20Hound%20of%20the%20Baskervilles%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20inclined%20to%20%E2%80%9Csupernatural%20explanation%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fprofiles%2Fcatherine-wynne-1320503%5C%22%3ECatherine%20Wynne%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20Associate%20Dean%20for%20Research%20and%20Enterprise%2C%20Faculty%20of%20Arts%2C%20Cultures%20and%20Education%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Finstitutions%2Funiversity-of-hull-1191%5C%22%3EUniversity%20of%20Hull%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EThis%20article%20is%20republished%20from%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%5C%22%3EThe%20Conversation%3C%2Fa%3E%20under%20a%20Creative%20Commons%20license.%20Read%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fhow-sherlock-holmes-ancient-egypt-and-a-mysterious-curse-inspired-agatha-christie-212156%5C%22%3Eoriginal%20article%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1698143435000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2018%2F05%2F22181116%2Fdownload-21.jpg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fbooks%2Fhow-sherlock-holmes-ancient-egypt-and-a-mysterious-curse-inspired-agatha-christie%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22By%20the%20early%201920s%2C%20Conan%20Doyle%20%E2%80%93%20though%20still%20publishing%20Sherlock%20Holmes%20stories%20%E2%80%93%20was%20coming%20to%20the%20end%20of%20his%20career%2C%20while%20Christie%E2%80%99s%20was%20just%20beginning.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22enga